MUDI explores issues faced by women working in menial / non-unionised jobs

Women Workers in Menial Jobs

by Wandoh Sam

l) Introduction

Menial or low skills jobs are those that fulfill needs which can not be taken care of by machines. Such jobs remain necessary in today's mechanical society in spite of wide scale mechanisation and automation. To avoid human exploitation and become more effective, workers must have the freedom to joint in economic and social planning. Yet, in a changing socioeconomic system, which is still undergoing transition from a pre industrial style to that of a developed industrial centre, we still find a number of people in menial jobs. This means that now, in spite of state efforts to develop the economy, the division of labour remains social pertaining to the class system inherited from the pre-industrial style of society.

These divisions continue dividing people, and most of them are in menial job. Olga Zaii
